› 1. W-bit as a quantization / robustness lab for real networks

  Right now: W-bit plays with synthetic tasks and synthetic weights.

  Next level: treat it as a microscope on real learned weights.

  Concept:

  Take small subnets from a real model (MLP blocks, attention projections, etc.).

  Quantize their weights into W-bit states (R levels) with your w-bit rules.

  Push real activation distributions through them.

  Measure:

  accuracy degradation,

  robustness to noise,

  RCP / steps as a compute cost proxy.

  Why it’s a level up

  You stop answering “What happens in this toy?” and start answering:

  “Given weights that actually solve real tasks, what does extra R buy me vs binary?”

  You get plots like:

  quality vs R,

  robustness vs R,

  RCP vs R,
  and can find sweet spots where W-bit dominates binary.

  MVP sketch

  Define a simple interface like:

  def wbit_eval_layer(W, x_batch, mode, R, sigma, trials) -> dict:
      # quantize W to W-bit, run exp, return success/rcp/loss stats


  Feed it:

  W from a small trained MLP (even MNIST / tiny transformer).

  x_batch sampled from its training/validation data.

  Log CSV with columns:

  layer_name, mode, R, sigma, success_rate, loss_delta, avg_rcp, n_effective, R_effective, mode_variant.

  Plot:

  loss_delta vs R at fixed sigma,

  robustness curves vs sigma for different R.

  2. Turn Phase 2 into a real “phase diagram” of W-bit

  Right now: you have nice sweeps, but they’re still “experiment reports”.

  Next level: treat W-bit like condensed-matter / stat-phys:

  Axes: (R_effective, sigma, density, layout) → phases:

  “Reliable routing”

  “Meta-stable but slow”

  “Chaotic / fail”

  Tasks

  Expand grids:

  For a fixed experiment (say Phase 2 ExpB grid), sweep:

  R_effective across a few values (3,5,7,9,11…),

  sigma range,

  maybe 2–3 densities.

  Define phase labels using thresholds:

  e.g. success_rate ≥ 0.9 = “good phase”

  success_rate in [0.1, 0.9) = “edge”

  < 0.1 = “fail”

  Emit a phase_diagram.csv with:

  R_effective, sigma, density, phase_label, success_rate, avg_rcp.

  Plot:

  heatmaps or contour lines R vs sigma, colored by phase label.

  Why it matters

  You’ll be able to say:

  “At these noise levels, you must go beyond binary; W-bit with R≈5–7 is the robust regime.”

  That’s a story you can sell to yourself, to Aeternum, to future hardware investors.

  3. Make adaptive actually intelligent (policy search)

  Current adaptive heuristic is hand-coded and simple (sigma thresholds → n).

  Next level: treat n_effective policy as a learned controller.

  Idea

  Parameterize policy: n_effective = f(sigma, weight_scale, maybe history; θ).

  Define objective:

  high success_rate, low RCP, low average R_effective.

  Run a small optimizer / search over θ:

  could be brute force over a small grid for now.

  MVP

  Define a tiny policy space:

  threshold sigma_t:

  if sigma < sigma_t → n=1

  else n=2 or 3.

  For each policy:

  run a reduced ExpB grid (few sigmas, weight scales),

  compute a scalar score:

  score = success_rate_mean - α * avg_R_effective - β * avg_rcp_normalized


  Pick best policy, log it as adaptive_policy_v1.

  Why it’s a step up

  Adaptive stops being “some heuristic you wrote at 2am” and becomes “the best found policy under a defined cost function”.

  You can later plug in more features (local signal quality, early failure signals, etc.).
  4. Repository evolution: from scripts to a “W-bit lab” library

  Right now: it’s a good script zoo.

  Next level: turn it into a clean lab toolkit:

  wbit_core/ – core types, network construction, stepping.

  wbit_experiments/ – exp_A, exp_B, exp_C as thin wrappers.

  wbit_analysis/ – analysis helpers reusable across new experiments.

  Mini roadmap

  Extract a minimal wbit.core module:

  mode, R_effective, net_mode, noise, etc.

  Remove duplicated logic (effective R, mode_variant) from individual scripts and centralize it.
  This doesn’t give new science, but it makes all the above extensions less painful.

  5. Prioritized “transcend” plan


  Phase diagram for ExpB
  Adaptive policy search v1

  Grid-search simple threshold policies over sigma, log best.
  Add derived energy/area metrics in analysis and re-plot.

  Refactor into W-bit lab


